...
```

Download the RPMs.

how user_loader  distinguish between the different user classes.
just like:
```python
@login_manager.user_loader
def load_user(user_id):
    if request.path == "/apiv1.0/admin/":
        return Admin.query.get(int(user_id))
    else:
        return User.query.get(int(user_id))
```
the same question https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26242922/flask-login-for-multiple-users

In the current docs, a Jinja template example for Flask Login is given as:

    {% if current_user.is_authenticated %}
      Hi {{ current_user.name }}!
    {% endif %}

Unfortunately, this code is broken and will always render the "Hi" text as it is missing the parantheses for the method call. Instead of *calling* the method `is_authenticated()`, it evaluates the method name `is_authenticated`, which exists, so the condition of the if clause is always true.

This is what is intended:

    {% if current_user.is_authenticated() %}
      Hi {{ current_user.name }}!
    {% endif %}

Let's hope, nobody copied the example to production code without checking ;-)

In one of my [projects](https://github.com/smarie/python-parsyfiles) I had to implement this function, I guess it could be useful to share in `typing_inspect`, and also to provide the equivalent for subclass tests, what do you think ? (I did not find any equivalent in `typing` nor in `typing_inspect`)

```python
from typing import Any, Type
from typing_inspect import is_union_type, get_args, get_origin

def robust_isinstance(inst: Any, typ: Type):
    """
    Similar to isinstance, but if 'typ' is a parametrized generic Type, it is first transformed into its base generic class so that the instance check works. It is also robust to Union and Any.

    :param inst: the instance to check against the type
    :param typ: the type
    :return:
    """
    if typ is Any:
        return True
    elif not is_union_type(typ):
        return isinstance(inst, get_origin(typ) or typ)
    else:
        typs = get_args(typ)
        if len(typs) > 0:
            return any(robust_isinstance(inst, t) for t in typs)
        else:
            return False
```

